    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA114-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">iḵtu āṟupārttu uṟṟa accattāṉ ṟōḻi talaivikku uraippāḷāyc ciṟaippuṟamākac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said while [HE] was behind the fence, as one who talks to HER, out of the fear she experienced upon seeing the path.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA114">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            veṇkōṭu koṇṭu viyalaṟai vaippavum</l>
<l>            paccūṉ keṇṭi vaḷḷukir muṇakkavu</l>
<l>            maṟukutoṟu pulāvañ ciṟukuṭi yaravam</l>
<l>            vaikik kēṭṭup paiyān ticiṉē</l>
<l>            yaḷitō tāṉē tōḻi yalkal </l>
<l>            vantōṉ maṉṟa kuṉṟa nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>            ṟuḷipeyal poṟitta puḷḷit toṉkarai</l>
<l>            porutirai nivappiṉ varumyā ṟañcuva</l>
<l>            līrnkura lurumi ṉārkali nallēṟu</l>
<l>            pāmpukavi ṉaḻikku mōṅkuvarai potti </l>
<l>            maiyiṉ maṭappiṭi yiṉaiyak</l>
<l>            kaiyūṉṟu piḻitaru kaḷiṟeṟin taṉṟē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>I am distressed on hearing, being kept [at home?]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vaiki</term>: thus the explanation given by T.V.G.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">the sound from the small hamlet, reeking of flesh in every street,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when they take the white tusk [and] place it on the wide rock</l>
<l rend="indent2">and when they cut off the fresh flesh [and] draw the sharp nails.</l>
<l>Ah, it [is] pitiful, friend, the night.<note place="foot">In line 5 and 6, syntax is unmarked and accordingly unclear. Perhaps it is best to take <term xml:lang="ta">alkal</term> as open-ended post-positioned subject of the <term xml:lang="ta">aḷitō</term> clause, and then read it as temporal specification of the following <term xml:lang="ta">vantōṉ</term>.</note></l>
<l>[At that time] he came indeed, the man from a land of hills.</l>
<l>I fear the river that comes when the dashing waves grow</l>
<l rend="indent2">over the marked(?) old shore, impressed by the dripping rain.</l>
<l>It threw down the elephant bull that comes down, trunk fixed,</l>
<l rend="indent3">for the cloud-like youthful elephant cow to despair,</l>
<l rend="indent2">covering the high mountain, where the bustling good stroke</l>
<l rend="indent2">of thunder with [its] wet voice destroys the beauty of snakes.</l>
        </lg>
